        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### → **85.0% of all stability-constant measurements were conducted at 25 °C.**\n\nHere is the full top-10 temperature distribution:\n\n| Temperature (°C) | Measurements | % of Total |\n|:-:|:-:|:-:|\n| 25.0 | 67,237 | 85.04% |\n| 20.0 | 6,845 | 8.66% |\n| 37.0 | 1,699 | 2.15% |\n| 30.0 | 919 | 1.16% |\n| 35.0 | 488 | 0.62% |\n| 18.0 | 482 | 0.61% |\n| 10.0 | 334 | 0.42% |\n| 40.0 | 324 | 0.41% |\n| 22.0 | 324 | 0.41% |\n| 15.0 | 197 | 0.25% |\n\n**Chemistry insight:** The overwhelming dominance of 25 °C (298.15 K) reflects its status as the standard reference temperature in solution thermodynamics. The 37 °C cluster (~2%) corresponds to physiological temperature, likely from bioinorganic and pharmaceutical studies. The 20 °C entries (~9%) are common in older European literature where \"room temperature\" was conventionally taken as 20 °C rather than 25 °C.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (SRD-46)*",
